04745nam a22005775i 9780774850414DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748504147 a10.59962/97807748504142doi  a(DE-B1597)661994  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJF801b.B446 2003eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a323.6 012211 aBeiner, Ronald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiberalism, Nationalism, Citizenship :bEssays on the Problem of Political Community /cRonald Beiner. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tCitizenship versus Liberalism -- tLiberalism, Nationalism, Citizenship: Three Models of Political Community -- tThe Fetish of Individuality: Richard Flathman’s Willfully Liberal Politics -- tCivic Resources in a Liberal Society: “Thick” and “Thin” Versions of Liberalism -- tFrom Community to Citizenship: The Quest for a Post-Liberal Public Philosophy -- tIs There Such a Thing As a Communitarian Political Philosophy? -- tCitizenship versus Nationalism -- tNationalism’s Challenge to Political Philosophy -- tRefl ections of a Diaspora Jew in Israel -- tHannah Arendt As a Critic of Nationalism -- tNational Self-Determination: Some Cautionary Remarks on the Rhetoric of Rights -- tCitizenship and Nationalism: Is Canada a “Real Country”? -- t1989: Nationalism, Internationalism, and the Nairn-Hobsbawm Debate -- tCivicism between Nationalism and Globalism: Some Refl ections on the Prob lem of Political Community -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiberals believe that the purpose of politics is to guarantee that individuals do not face unfair impediments in pursuing the lives they choose for themselves. Nationalists believe that the purpose of politics is to ensure that a people's sense of authentic nationhood wins full expression in powers of collective sovereignty or self-rule. Both of these forms of political commitment yield world-transforming political philosophies, but do either of these visions do adequate justice to a philosophically robust ideal of shared citizenship and civic membership? In Liberalism, Nationalism, Citizenship, Ronald Beiner engages critically with a wide range of important political thinkers and current debates in light of the Aristotelian idea that shared citizenship is an essential human calling. Virtually every aspect of contemporary political experience -- globalization, international migration, secessionist movements, the politics of multiculturalism -- pose urgent challenges to modern citizenship. Beiner's work on the philosophy of citizenship is essential reading not just for students of politics and political philosophy, but for all those who rightly sense that these kinds of recent challenges demand an ambitious rethinking of the nature of political community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenship. 0aCivil society. 0aFree enterprise. 0aLiberalism. 0aNationalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485041440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850414/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-